BLUETONGUE - EUROPE (04): BTV-8, UK (ENGLAND)
*********************************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.promedmail.org>
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>
Date: Sun 27 Jan 2008
Source: Farmers Weekly Interactive [edited]
<http://www.fwi.co.uk/Articles/2008/01/27/109169/defra-bluetongue-announcement-expected-to-confirm-new-cases-tomorrow.html>

DEFRA (Department of Environment, Food and Rural Affairs) is expected to
make an announcement tomorrow [28 Jan 2008] which will confirm new cases of
bluetongue in Shropshire and Cheshire.
A source close to DEFRA told Farmers Weekly that the cases which had been
discovered in the last few days were not believed to have been found in
imported animals, suggesting the animals had been infected by UK midges
carrying the disease.
It is not yet known what affect the new cases will have on the movement
regulations currently in place, but it could mean the extension of the
protection zone into Wales and further towards the southwest of England,
possibly as far south as Bristol.
This could leave west Wales and the far south west of England as peninsulas
of non-restricted stock. It will also have an impact on vaccination plans,
with more farmers likely to be in the zone due to receive vaccine 1st. This
could dilute the amount of vaccine available to farmers in the 1st wave of
vaccination due to begin in May 2008 and have serious consequences for
virus control this spring and summer 2008. More news will follow as we
receive it.
--
communicated by:
Sabine Zentis
Castleview Pedigree English Longhorns
Gut Laach
52385 Nideggen, Germany
