[In case this piece of information is indeed officially confirmed, it means
that the vector maintains (even if reduced) activity during the winter
months. This is bad news, with expected flare-ups of the disease and its
possible further spread during 2008 into susceptible, sero-negative animal
populations.
According to available information, continental BTV-8 affected countries,
predominantly France, experience also some continued vector activity during
the current winter (2008). Planning for the shortly due mass-vaccination
should be adapted to the unfolding situation, targeting protection by the
immunization of susceptible animals within broader areas than initially
suggested, namely also in BT-receptive areas beyond the declared protection
and surveillance zones. The vaccination should preferably cover more than
80 per cent of the susceptible stock.
The EU BTV restriction zones map, updated on 22 Jan 2008, is available at
<http://ec.europa.eu/food/animal/diseases/controlmeasures/BlueTongue_RestrictedZones_2008.jpg>.
- Mod.AS]
